ois. This type of construction, especially in phrases such as “needs washed,” is a staple of Pittsburgh-ese. There is some evidence that this need/want + V-en construction might have originated from Scots English. Additionally, while not linked specifically to any sociolinguistic factors, this type of construction is most typically seen amongst Caucasian speakers.%0a%3c %0a%3c This construction can also lend itself to more flexibility. While in Standard American English, verbs such as “want” and “like” are volitional – relate to the subject’s will or desire, using the need/want + V-en construction, this is not necessarily the case. Sometimes these verbs are used in a way that is not volitional to the subject. For example, using this construction, one could say “These kids want scolded.” The meaning of this sentence is not that the kids actually desire to be scolded, but that the speaker desires to scold them. This is not an acceptable way to express this meaning by Standard American English rules, but the meaning is still clear. This is just one example of the added flexibility associated with this construction.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/needs-washed#who-says-this%0a%3c Thomas E. Murray; and Beth Lee Simon. At the intersection of regional and social dialects: The case of like + past participle in American English. American Speech, 77(1): 32–69. 2002.%0a%3c Keith Brown; and Martin Millar. Auxiliary verbs in Edinburgh speech. Transactions of the Philological Society, 78(1): 81–133. November 1980.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Commen